WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.440
Thank you. So I'll be speaking about AI for Gaming. And what you see here is a software

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:16.780
called Gatai playing a video game called Christmas 3. And this is from one of our training sessions.

00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:23.240
This was when we tried to do this brute force, something that didn't work. And we'll get

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:31.160
back to why that didn't work shortly. And a little bit of history. First, Gato is a

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:38.880
web portal for game creators. And Gato, then when they approached me about this project

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:49.520
became Gato AI, which turned into Gatai and then Gatai the AI. And Gato means cat in Spanish.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:56.959
And I live and work in Argentina. And because it means that that's why Gatai is a feline,

00:00:56.959 --> 00:01:07.400
as you can see here. And that sort of stuck with throughout the project. Christmas 3 is

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:11.720
a puzzle game that you can play online, you can look it up and you can play it directly

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:19.559
in the browser. And the purpose of the game is to move any of these tiles, either vertically

00:01:19.559 --> 00:01:27.839
or horizontally, so that they line up in groups of two, three or four, no three, four or five.

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:33.879
And then you get different scores based on that. So it's not a very complex game. And

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:41.480
I'll just show here, these would be two valid moves to make on this board. And there are

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:50.959
10 different types of tiles. And the board is 10 by 6. And that is sort of why the brute

00:01:50.959 --> 00:02:00.919
force approach will not work because you are looking at 10 to the 60th combinations here.

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:08.440
And so we had to look for strategies on how to reduce this. This is what is called the

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:16.559
state space. So the total number of possible configurations of the board. And that's an

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:22.119
important concept in reinforcement learning, which is what we're going to be using to play

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:32.119
this game. Now, so to put this number in context, this is, you know, it's more than the number

00:02:32.119 --> 00:02:38.800
of atoms on Earth, less than the observable universe. And it's actually quite a bit bigger

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:47.800
than chess that actually surprised me when I looked at this. We can talk about why after,

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:52.119
but that actually surprised me. It's more complex than chess when you just look at the

00:02:52.119 --> 00:03:01.080
state spaces. So what is a state space? It's a configuration of the board. In our case,

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:07.160
when you use reinforcement learning, there's an algorithm called Q-learning that totally

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:13.919
talks about state space, action space. There's a reward, which is essentially the score and

00:03:13.919 --> 00:03:18.880
the resulting state. So state space is what is on the board. Action space is what you

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:24.399
can do with that. And the rewards is the score. And then the resulting state is what does

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:31.160
the board look like when you are done, when you have made your move. And this goes into

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:38.440
a formula and the algorithm can converge and then solve the game essentially. So we had

00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:43.919
to reduce the state space. And we had three strategies for that. The first one was to

00:03:43.919 --> 00:03:51.399
play one type at a time. So I do stars first and then I do the red balls and then I do

00:03:51.399 --> 00:04:05.080
the little candy sticks or whatever it was. And then that will take this. I've just arbitrarily

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:14.919
put A through G on the board here. It will reduce it to 2 to the 60th, which is still

00:04:14.919 --> 00:04:23.799
far too much for a brute force approach, but it is some magnitudes less. And this is actually

00:04:23.799 --> 00:04:28.959
quite convenient if you're going to program it, because this is a binary number that you

00:04:28.959 --> 00:04:35.079
can pass through functions and have fun with. The other one, probably the most important

00:04:35.079 --> 00:04:44.760
one is windowing, which is if you create a board that's a 3 by 2 here, you can put that,

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:53.200
you can slide that across the bigger board. And then, you know, if you know how to play

00:04:53.200 --> 00:05:02.679
this pattern on the left, you can use that on any part of the bigger board. And then

00:05:02.679 --> 00:05:08.480
there's transposition because the game is symmetrical. If you know how to play the position

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:15.440
on the left, you can also play the position on the right. So that reduces our spaces quite

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:23.399
a bit and we can take advantage of that. So I trained the model on these sub boards

00:05:23.399 --> 00:05:33.160
and I did this synthetically and theoretically, I got as far as 5 by 4. And after that, the

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:41.239
algorithm would not converge. So I left it overnight and it didn't converge. I used POSIT

00:05:41.239 --> 00:05:48.920
Cloud to do this. So I had standard and commodity hardware. You can probably tweak more out

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:56.519
of it, but it's going to start costing money just about at that point. So those were the

00:05:56.519 --> 00:06:02.440
models we had available. I trained the first two to begin with, that doesn't take very

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:10.040
long. And then, you know, you want to do some spot checks. So here's one where, you know,

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:17.399
I want to know that it makes an intelligent move. You call predict on the state space

00:06:17.399 --> 00:06:24.279
that you've created. And you know, it says B1 to C1, which is the blue you see on the

00:06:24.279 --> 00:06:30.679
screen here. So here's one where there isn't a reasonable move to make in a 3 by 3 grid

00:06:30.679 --> 00:06:36.799
and it comes back with a pass. But so it's been trained to act when there isn't a reasonable

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:44.320
move to make. The other thing that was interesting was, you know, does it actually think ahead?

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:51.119
And it turns out that it does. Here, if you give it the board on the left, it will propose

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:58.799
A1 to B1. And we assume that that's in preparation for the next move, which will score then 50

00:06:58.799 --> 00:07:07.279
points in this case. And then what happens when you have competing moves? The one to

00:07:07.279 --> 00:07:15.760
the left here will score 50 points. The one down will score 100 points the way the scoring

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:22.239
system is. And it actually chooses the highest scoring move. So at this point, we had trained

00:07:22.239 --> 00:07:28.399
the 3 by 3 and the 3 by 4s. And it seemed reasonable that, you know, we were actually,

00:07:28.399 --> 00:07:37.679
this actually worked. As a concept, we trained the rest of the subboards up until 5 by 4

00:07:37.679 --> 00:07:45.040
is how far we got. And then I wanted to do this. I wanted to interact with the GUI. I

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:51.519
wanted to actually play the game in the browser. And for that, I used Selenium with a Chrome

00:07:51.519 --> 00:07:57.839
browser. I used Python for the connecting code because I couldn't get the R package

00:07:57.839 --> 00:08:04.000
to work. There is an R package, R-Selenium. It didn't work on my hardware then. It actually

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:10.480
works on the hardware I'm bringing today because I've switched in the meantime. This is a MacBook.

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:15.799
I was working on a Chromebook at the time. So it depends if you have the right drivers

00:08:15.799 --> 00:08:23.480
and you're sort of beholden to the hardware here. So the way this works is the AI will

00:08:23.480 --> 00:08:32.679
start the game. It sends a URL to the driver, which then loads the game in Chrome. And it

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:38.200
then takes a screenshot that gets sent back to the AI. The AI analyzes the screenshot

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:45.359
and sends moves back to Chrome through that driver. That's a Selenium driver. So this

00:08:45.359 --> 00:08:51.960
is what we get in. This is our raw material. And of course, we have to cut it into different

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:58.840
tiles to be able to evaluate what would be reasonable moves to make. Now, the problem

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:05.159
here is that when you do this, the tiles, when you calculate the coordinates, you come

00:09:05.159 --> 00:09:12.599
up with decimals, which means that depending on where you are on this board, the tile is

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:18.719
going to be slightly smaller and bigger, which is why you can't actually do a direct comparison.

00:09:18.719 --> 00:09:25.599
So we had to create a vision model as well. We used magic for that. That's a package for

00:09:25.599 --> 00:09:34.440
image manipulation and then multinomial logistic regression. And we, you know, it was relatively

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:42.200
easy in that we could just count the number of red, green, and blue in the image. And

00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:48.039
that was enough information to be able to distinguish them. And the way this works is

00:09:48.039 --> 00:09:57.679
you give it an image file or an image in memory. You read it here, I printed it out. It's a

00:09:57.679 --> 00:10:05.799
star. And you can also call predict. This is a regression model. And if you ask for

00:10:05.799 --> 00:10:12.039
the probability, it will give you a probability for every category. And for our purposes,

00:10:12.039 --> 00:10:16.640
you know, we're going to choose the first one, obviously, you get a non-zero probability

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:24.880
for every category, because that's how the algorithm works. So when I had this, I was

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:31.919
able to play the game on the board and we tried out the different strategies. And we

00:10:31.919 --> 00:10:38.440
got 42.5. That's the mean score per move, which I think is the only reasonable metric

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:46.840
to use here. There's a version of the game where you can play in a certain time, but

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:54.440
then again, you're really testing your hardware, not the AI that you'd created. So I chalked

00:10:54.440 --> 00:11:08.119
this up as a victory for Gatai. And then comes the question, why do all this? And of

00:11:08.119 --> 00:11:17.080
course, the main one for me was bragging rights. There's some nerds play video games and bigger

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:22.080
nerds create them. But if you write the code that plays the video games that these super

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:31.359
nerds write, then I think you are a member of the geekhood. Then the other thing was,

00:11:31.359 --> 00:11:38.400
I had taken their products from their websites. You know, this is wild caught product from

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:47.159
their catalog. And I had applied AI to it. That is what I wanted to do. And I wanted

00:11:47.159 --> 00:11:51.119
this to be a portfolio project. I wanted to go back to the company and say, you know,

00:11:51.159 --> 00:12:00.159
there are some business cases for you where we can use AI. And the game that I analyzed

00:12:00.159 --> 00:12:05.080
is not one where you have an opponent, but it's relatively easy to see how you could

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:13.640
do that. But I did implement an assistant. Let's see if I can get this to run. And here

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:26.840
I am actually playing the game on the board. And I'm trying not to make too good moves

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:37.400
and huddling a little. And at some point, Gatai will detect that I'm stuck and it will,

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:50.440
like Clippy, show up and propose some moves. This is also done with Selenium, because you

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:55.799
can send JavaScript all the way through into the browser, and then the JavaScript will

00:12:55.799 --> 00:13:04.520
paint the Gatai logo and write out this and the arrows and everything. So that point of

00:13:04.599 --> 00:13:12.359
view, it's quite powerful. But what really caught their interest was the idea that how

00:13:12.359 --> 00:13:17.559
about we apply generative AI to this? How about we do this at scale? We can scan in

00:13:17.559 --> 00:13:24.919
all the games in your catalog, and we can make an LLM that will then create custom games

00:13:25.719 --> 00:13:33.640
for your users. So I know what kind of game you'd like to play. Here is one that is made

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:41.880
exactly for you by our system. And then they asked me how much that would cost. And I said,

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:51.719
you know, maybe $5 million, maybe 10. And then they asked when I could submit my last invoice.

00:13:51.719 --> 00:14:01.080
And that was the end of my career in the gaming industry. Now, I have a day job. I am a teacher.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:08.200
I teach data science at the university. And I thought of how to reuse this project or project

00:14:08.200 --> 00:14:14.119
like this in my teaching, because we did a lot of work. We did a lot of simulations.

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:22.440
We got results back. If you have an empirical approach, you will say, well, from these results,

00:14:23.400 --> 00:14:30.359
we can extrapolate these rules with a certain p-value. For example, one of them was

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:38.440
there's always going to be a two-move combination that is reasonable to make on this board.

00:14:39.479 --> 00:14:44.039
We have a p-value for that. Now you can take that to the next level and say, well, that's a

00:14:44.039 --> 00:14:52.520
conjecture. Can we prove this mathematically? And you can. And then, you know, if you want to follow

00:14:52.520 --> 00:15:00.280
that trail, what's the minimum number of tile types you need to have for that to be true?

00:15:01.799 --> 00:15:06.039
And when you're done with that, you can play with the geometry on the board. You know, we're doing

00:15:06.039 --> 00:15:13.880
six by 10. What if you do one by 10? What are the rules then, mathematically? Oh, one by infinity.

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:18.119
Infinity is always fun to work with when you're proving stuff mathematically.

00:15:19.479 --> 00:15:24.599
Of course, all the code we wrote should sit in a package, so we can talk about package development.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:32.679
I implemented the state spaces as S. That's not correct, actually. It's S3 classes.

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:41.880
And I implemented the robot as R6 classes. There is a reason for that. What are the pros and cons

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:49.559
of each type of class structure that we have available? Graphics processing is an important

00:15:49.559 --> 00:15:57.080
topic because images are data too, and we should be able to analyze them and manipulate them and

00:15:58.039 --> 00:16:05.640
use them in data science. And browser automation, I think, is a cool topic.

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:10.840
So, you know, there's a couple of tracks here. There's one very theoretical track,

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:17.799
and there's one more engineering track, maybe some system integration. And of course,

00:16:17.799 --> 00:16:22.359
we have to write this up. We have to create this presentation, use Quarto for that.

00:16:23.320 --> 00:16:31.000
So I think there's enough here for one semester seminar for a group of students that I have.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:37.239
And I'm hoping to be able to distribute this so that the guys who like mathematical proofs

00:16:37.239 --> 00:16:43.080
get to work on that, and the people who want to work on more engineering stuff can do that.

00:16:44.039 --> 00:16:51.320
And then since we do this as a group project, we also learn how to work in an interdisciplinary

00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:58.679
field, interdisciplinary team. So this is how I tend to use it going forward

00:16:59.799 --> 00:17:08.680
as a teacher. And that's what I had for you today. Thank you for your attention.

00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:16.920
Very interesting. I can't wait to go and play some Christmas tree.

00:17:19.719 --> 00:17:26.199
Quick question from the audience. You mentioned that the model got an average score of 42.5 per

00:17:26.199 --> 00:17:30.599
move. Did you get a chance to compare that to an average human player?

00:17:31.319 --> 00:17:37.640
Only to myself. Yeah. And I got, you know, 20 per move or something like that.

00:17:38.599 --> 00:17:48.920
Okay. Interesting. Okay. So do you have any thoughts to apply this concept to other kinds

00:17:48.920 --> 00:17:55.640
of games or have you looked into that for the future? Yeah. So this is a puzzle game.

00:17:57.079 --> 00:18:04.439
And then, you know, this kind of algorithm works really well for a puzzle game. And you can also

00:18:04.439 --> 00:18:11.079
use the Selenium connector to actually play it in the browser, which I think is very powerful.

00:18:12.359 --> 00:18:21.719
If you want to do space invaders, for example, then things need to move faster. So you need

00:18:21.719 --> 00:18:27.000
to intercept. You can't really play it in the browser with a Selenium setup and take a screenshot

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:32.599
and evaluate. You're not going to have that much time. So for that, the solution I have would be

00:18:32.599 --> 00:18:39.640
to use, there's a platform called Unity, which is used to create games. And it has actually has

00:18:39.640 --> 00:18:49.239
a plugin for AI agents. So then you bypass the rendering on screen of everything. And you

00:18:49.239 --> 00:18:54.199
actually play the game synthetically just before it goes to the screen and goes to the hardware.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:00.359
So then you can actually train models for faster games, so to speak.

00:19:01.319 --> 00:19:07.719
Very cool. One last question, short one. How long did this project take, start to finish,

00:19:07.719 --> 00:19:13.239
if you're willing to say? Yeah, three weeks.

00:19:14.599 --> 00:19:22.199
Very interesting. Thank you so much. Yeah, absolutely.

00:19:30.359 --> 00:19:30.859
Thank you.

